<button class="tw:ai-button  ai-simplify-button module-spacing js-inline-ai-simplify-button p-10 ml-5"> Quick Summary</button>




































  
































<button class="tw:ai-button  ai-ask-button module-spacing js-inline-ai-ask-button p-10 ml-5"> Ask Anything</button>

</div>
                <!--[BEFORE-ARTICLE]--><span class="marker before-article"></span><section data-level="1" id="ref1"><!--[PREMOD1]--><span class="marker PREMOD1 mod-inline"></span><p class="topic-paragraph"><strong><span id="ref1311851"></span>Bayt al-Hikmah</strong>,  royal <a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/library" class="md-crosslink autoxref " data-show-preview="true">library</a> maintained by the <a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/Abbasid-caliphate" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">Abbasid caliphs</a> during their reign in <a href="https://www.britannica.com/place/Baghdad" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">Baghdad</a>.</p><!--[MOD1]--><span class="marker MOD1 mod-inline"></span></section>           <!--[H2]--><span class="marker h2"></span><section data-level="1" id="ref356366"> <h2 class="h1">History as the royal library in Baghdad</h2> <!--[PREMOD2]--><span class="marker PREMOD2 mod-inline"></span><p class="topic-paragraph">The foundation of Bayt al-Hikmah coincided with the rise of Baghdad as the capital of the <a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/Islamic-world" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">Islamic world</a> and the subsequent reception of Persian <a class="md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off mw" data-term="culture" href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/culture" data-type="MW">culture</a> into the Arab court of the Abbasids. The site of Baghdad was chosen by the second Abbasid caliph, <a href="https://www.britannica.com/biography/al-Mansur-Abbasid-caliph" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">al-Manr</a> (reigned 754775), to replace <a href="https://www.britannica.com/place/Damascus" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">Damascus</a>, whose status as the <a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/Umayyad-dynasty-Islamic-history" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">Umayyad</a> capital had made it difficult for the new <a class="md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off mw" data-term="dynasty" href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/dynasty" data-type="MW">dynasty</a> to fully uproot the one that it had overthrown in 750 <span class="text-smallcaps">ce</span>. But Baghdad, located near the former Sasanian capital of <a href="https://www.britannica.com/place/Ctesiphon-ancient-city-Iraq" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">Ctesiphon</a>, was also in the heart of a predominantly Persian populace. Instead of repressing what remained of Sasanian society, al-Manr absorbed it into the new <a class="md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off mw" data-term="bureaucratic" href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/bureaucratic" data-type="MW">bureaucratic</a> structure and portrayed Abbasid rule as the revival of the <a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/Sasanian-dynasty" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">Sasanian empire</a>.</p><!--[MOD2]--><span class="marker MOD2 mod-inline"></span>  <!--[PREMOD3]--><span class="marker PREMOD3 mod-inline"></span><p class="topic-paragraph">Bayt al-Hikmah served as an arm of the caliphal <a class="md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off mw" data-term="bureaucracy" href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/bureaucracy" data-type="MW">bureaucracy</a> and appears to have been modeled on an earlier Sasanian practice. Persians in the early Islamic era, writing in Arabic, indicated that <em>buyt al-ikmah</em> (literally houses of wisdom) followed in the fashion of Sasanian nobility. Middle Persian literature also refers directly to the storage of books pertaining to <a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/Zoroastrianism" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">Zoroastrian</a> religion, Sasanian dynastic history, and scientific knowledge for medical and administrative purposes. The storage space was called a <em>ganj</em> (treasury), a term equivalent to the Arabic <em>khiznah</em>.</p><!--[MOD3]--><span class="marker MOD3 mod-inline"></span> <!--[PREMOD4]--><span class="marker PREMOD4 mod-inline"></span><p class="topic-paragraph">The collection of Bayt al-Hikmah, like those of its Sasanian predecessors, was intended to reflect the <a class="md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off mw" data-term="continuity" href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/continuity" data-type="MW">continuity</a> of Persian heritage in the current ruling dynasty. It included Arabic translations of Middle Persian chronicles and astrological histories that were developed by Sasanian astrologers (<em>see</em> <a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/astrology/Astrology-after-the-Hellenistic-period#ref35975" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">astrology: In&nbsp;Sasanian&nbsp;Iran</a>). The reproduction of earlier works at Bayt al-Hikmah was evident in its staffing, which included copyists and bookbinders alongside library administrators. Some amount of translation activityalmost exclusively from <a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/Persian-language" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">Persian</a> into <a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/Arabic-language" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">Arabic</a>also took place, but it was not among the primary functions of Bayt al-Hikmah.</p><!--[MOD4]--><span class="marker MOD4 mod-inline"></span> <!--[PREMOD5]--><span class="marker PREMOD5 mod-inline"></span><p class="topic-paragraph">Bayt al-Hikmah, like Baghdad itself, was greatly enriched under the reign of <a href="https://www.britannica.com/biography/Harun-al-Rashid" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">Hrn al-Rashd</a> (786809). The caliph and his court were flush with wealth from tributes paid across the empire. The splendour of Baghdad at that time was immortalized in <a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/The-Thousand-and-One-Nights" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true"><em>The Thousand and One Nights</em></a>. The narrator of one story, relating the experience of one of his brothers, describes a palace of the utmost beauty and elegance, paved with marble, hung with curtains and having in the midst of it a flower garden whose like he had never seen and hails the Caliphs generosity and natural beneficence and princely wisdom. Hrns reign was also the height of power for the Persian <a class="md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off mw" data-term="aristocracy" href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/aristocracy" data-type="MW">aristocracy</a>, with the dynastic <a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/Barmakids" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">Barmakid</a> family serving as the empires chief administrators (<a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/vizier" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">viziers</a>). Patronage of the arts and sciencesand, of course, luxurypoured in not only from the caliph but also from the viziers and the other courtiers.</p><!--[MOD5]--><span class="marker MOD5 mod-inline"></span> <!--[PREMOD6]--><span class="marker PREMOD6 mod-inline"></span><div class="assemblies"><div class="w-100 assembly-container"><figure class="md-assembly m-0 mb-md-0 card card-borderless print-false" data-assembly-id="279009" data-asm-type="image"><div class="md-assembly-wrapper card-media" data-type="image"><a href="https://cdn.britannica.com/00/242300-050-95292A75/page-book-of-ingenious-devices-banu-musa-brothers-house-of-wisdom.jpg" class="gtm-assembly-link position-relative d-flex align-items-center justify-content-center media-overlay-link card-media" data-href="/media/1/56961/279009"><picture><source media="(min-width: 680px)" srcset="https://cdn.britannica.com/00/242300-050-95292A75/page-book-of-ingenious-devices-banu-musa-brothers-house-of-wisdom.jpg?w=300"><img src="https://cdn.britannica.com/00/242300-050-95292A75/page-book-of-ingenious-devices-banu-musa-brothers-house-of-wisdom.jpg?w=300" alt="The Book of Ingenious Devices" data-width="1600" data-height="1260" loading="eager"></picture><button class="magnifying-glass btn btn-circle position-absolute shadow btn-white top-10 right-10" aria-label="Zoom in"><em class="material-icons link-blue" data-icon="zoom_in"></em></button></a></div><figcaption class="card-body"><div class="md-assembly-caption text-muted font-14 font-serif line-clamp"><span><a class="gtm-assembly-link md-assembly-title font-weight-bold d-inline font-sans-serif mr-5 media-overlay-link" href="https://cdn.britannica.com/00/242300-050-95292A75/page-book-of-ingenious-devices-banu-musa-brothers-house-of-wisdom.jpg" data-href="/media/1/56961/279009"><em>The Book of Ingenious Devices</em></a><span>Pages from the <em>The Book of Ingenious Devices</em> (850 <span class="text-smallcaps">ce</span>), an illustrated work about a variety of mechanical devices, written by the Ban Ms brothers, three Persian scholars who studied at Bayt al-Hikmah (House of Wisdom).</span><button class="js-more-btn d-none btn btn-unstyled font-12 bg-white js-content" aria-label="Toggle more/less fact data"><span class="link-blue">(more)</span></button></span></div></figcaption></figure></div></div><p class="topic-paragraph">Bayt al-Hikmah reached its zenith under Hrns son <a href="https://www.britannica.com/biography/al-Mamun" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">al-Mamn</a> (reigned 813833), who expanded both the activities undertaken at the library as well as the types of scholars associated with it. <a href="https://www.britannica.com/biography/al-Khwarizmi" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">Muammad ibn Ms al-Khwrizm</a>, a mathematician and astronomer frequently credited as the father of <a href="https://www.britannica.com/science/algebra" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">algebra</a>, was perhaps the best-known figure <a class="md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off mw" data-term="affiliated" href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/affiliated" data-type="MW">affiliated</a> with Bayt al-Hikmah at this time. Other prominent scholars were also involved with Bayt al-Hikmah during al-Mamns reign, including Yay ibn Ab Manr al-Munajjim, the astronomer, and the Ban Ms brothers, who made essential strides in the field of <a href="https://www.britannica.com/science/mechanics" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">mechanics</a>. It is unclear, however, how much knowledge production was undertaken by these scholars at Bayt al-Hikmah rather than elsewhere.</p><!--[MOD6]--><span class="marker MOD6 mod-inline"></span> <!--[PREMOD7]--><span class="marker PREMOD7 mod-inline"></span><p class="topic-paragraph">But it was also al-Mamns reign that brought about a change in wind for Bayt al-Hikmah, which had hitherto specialized in Persian knowledge. In the final years of his reign, he undertook a dramatic shift in the imperial <a class="md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off mw" data-term="ideology" href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/ideology" data-type="MW">ideology</a>. He <a class="md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off mw" data-term="endorsed" href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/endorsed" data-type="MW">endorsed</a> an Islamic theology that stressed <a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/free-will" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">free will</a> and <a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/dialectic-logic" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">dialectical reasoning</a> (<em>see</em> <a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/kalam-Islam" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">kalm</a>; <a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/Mutazilah" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">Mutazilah</a>). In an <a class="md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off mw" data-term="ironic" href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/ironic" data-type="MW">ironic</a> show of force, al-Mamn engaged in an inquisition (the <a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/mihnah" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true"><em>minah</em></a>) and persecuted those who would not conform. The <a class="md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off mw" data-term="intellectual" href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/intellectual" data-type="MW">intellectual</a> weaponry of the inquisition was supplied by the import of Hellenistic thought and the translation of <a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/Greek-philosophy" class="md-crosslink autoxref " data-show-preview="true">Greek philosophy</a> into Arabic, which al-Mamn had begun sponsoring in the years prior to his conversion.</p><div class="module-spacing">
    <DIV class="marketing-INLINE_SUBSCRIPTION marketing-content" data-marketing-id="INLINE_SUBSCRIPTION"><style> .student-promo-banner-wrapper {
