</DIV></div><!--[MOD7]--><span class="marker MOD7 mod-inline"></span> <!--[PREMOD8]--><span class="marker PREMOD8 mod-inline"></span><p class="topic-paragraph">Although it is unknown whether the <em>minah</em> had any direct impact on Bayt al-Hikmah, mention of the library ends almost entirely after the death of al-Mamn in 833. Tensions between the <a href="https://www.britannica.com/place/Caliphate" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">caliphate</a> and the old establishment continued into the reign of <a href="https://www.britannica.com/biography/al-Mutasim" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">al-Mutaim</a> (833842) and forced him to move the capital from Baghdad to nearby <a href="https://www.britannica.com/place/Samarra" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">Smarr</a>. Bayt al-Hikmah remained intact in Baghdad, but its association with al-Mamn in 10th-century texts may indicate that its collection was not supplemented after the capital was moved to Smarr. Whatever may have remained of the collection in 1258 was destroyed in the <a href="https://www.britannica.com/place/Mongol-empire" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">Mongol</a> sack of Baghdad.</p><!--[MOD8]--><span class="marker MOD8 mod-inline"></span>  </section> <!--[H3]--><span class="marker h3"></span><section data-level="1" id="ref356367"> <h2 class="h1">Legacy and myth as an academy</h2> <!--[PREMOD9]--><span class="marker PREMOD9 mod-inline"></span><p class="topic-paragraph">In modern times the library became a symbol of the scientific enterprise and imperial glory of the early Islamic period. It is frequently imagined as a centre of scholarship and collaboration for the greatest minds in <a href="https://www.britannica.com/place/Baghdad" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">Baghdad</a> and its environs as well as the heart of a <a class="md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off mw" data-term="robust" href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/robust" data-type="MW">robust</a> translation movement of <a href="https://www.britannica.com/art/Persian-literature" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">Persian</a>, <a href="https://www.britannica.com/art/Greek-literature" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">Greek</a>, and <a href="https://www.britannica.com/art/Syriac-literature" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">Syriac literature</a> into the <a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/Arabic-language" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">Arabic language</a>. Some historians have even gone as far as to describe it as an <a href="https://www.britannica.com/topic/academy-organization" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">academy</a>.</p><!--[MOD9]--><span class="marker MOD9 mod-inline"></span>  <!--[PREMOD10]--><span class="marker PREMOD10 mod-inline"></span><p class="topic-paragraph">Although scholarship and translation indeed flourished in 8th- and 9th-century Baghdad, and some of that activity took place in association with the library and its collection, there is little evidence that Bayt al-Hikmah was at the centre of any of these trends. The translation of Greek literature into Arabicperhaps the most cited activity identified with Bayt al-Hikmahtook place elsewhere entirely, as did the work of Greco-Arabic translators such as <a href="https://www.britannica.com/biography/Hunayn-ibn-Ishaq" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">unayn ibn Isq</a> and <a href="https://www.britannica.com/biography/al-Kindi" class="md-crosslink " data-show-preview="true">Yaqb ibn Isq al-ab al-Kind</a>.</p><div class="js-qf-module qf-module px-40 px-sm-20 py-15 mx-auto module-spacing font-14 bg-gray-50 rounded">

		<div class="facts-list mt-10">
			<div class="">

					<div class="js-fact mb-10 line-clamp clamp-3">
						<dl>
								<dt>Arabic: </dt>
								<dd>House of Wisdom</dd>
								</dl>
						<button class="js-more-btn d-none btn btn-unstyled font-12 bg-gray-50" aria-label="Toggle more/less fact data">
							<em class="js-content link-blue">(Show&nbsp;more)</em>
